			<wp:comment_author_url>http://www.anthroblog.tadmcilwraith.com</wp:comment_author_url>
			<wp:comment_author_IP>174.7.102.169</wp:comment_author_IP>
			<wp:comment_date>2011-01-30 14:59:52</wp:comment_date>
			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2011-01-30 18:59:52</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[I too find that it is hard to get students to wrap their head around allegories as explanations.  My context is the teaching of mythology.  What I read here is a description of contemporary mythology or, perhaps, contemporary mythologizing as a process.  These graphic novels are 'myth-like.'

I'm using a particular definition of myth, of course.  It's one that says myths shouldn't be read as falsehoods.  Rather, myths transmit cultural beliefs and values.  But, more than transmitting them, myths are used to debate critical social issues.  Your final sentence captures it: 'every [myth] ... is a chance to re-evaluate morals and values.'
]]></wp:comment_content>
