			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2011-01-30 18:54:31</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[Further, I'd raise at this point too the notion that 9/11 was a conspiracy.  That mythologizing of the 9/11 events fits perfectly within the mythological motif index developed years ago by Stith Thompson.  Like stories such as the X-Files, there is a pervasive theme in American mythology of the evil monster - where the government itself is the evil monster which holds unobtainable knowledge (divine knowledge, if you will).  In this case, it's the the government knowing that it was responsible for 9/11.  In the case of the X-Files, it's proof about the existence of aliens.  In the X-Files, you have a culture in the person of Fox Mulder.  He's the truth seeker.  The 9/11 culture hero is harder to identify in a single person.  It may be in the social media collective.

Thompson noted that evil beings restricting information from a group of people, and a culture hero determined to get that information and/or slay the monster, is a mythological trope found cross-culturally.

What are the truths and values contained in this story?  The people are always pitted against the government, I suppose.  Other themes are bound to come to your insightful imagination.]]></wp:comment_content>
