			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2011-04-13 16:16:02</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[Ok, so what you're saying is that the adverts are a part of the narrative or rather complement it in some way?
However, from what I can tell by reading older Batman and Superman comics, these kinds of adverts were not exaxtly new at the time Amazing Fantasy #15 was published.
While there is merit in your assertion of complementing the story-line with advertising, I think it is much less some kind of regularity, but rather the exception. After all, these kinds of ads - bodybuilding, get-rich-quick and cheap toys - have been present in a large amount of comic books up to then - and they most certainly did not always complement the story in this remarkable fashion as you present here.
Neither was Spider-Man specifically tailored to attract that advertising, nor the advertising tailored specifically for Spider-Man.
I don't think that the adverts tell us much about the graphic narrative and its reception, but rather that they tell us something about the audience comic books -largely- had at the time

Just my opinion, of course.]]></wp:comment_content>
