			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2012-05-15 15:06:28</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[I read this book today in Norwegian. It was beautiful but so very sad and troubling that I wanted to find out what other people thought. I found this article really helpful in framing my own reading.

Isn't there also a suggestion towards the end of the book that Jon wanted Bjørn to fall? That's why he said those words just as Bjørn was going to jump, in order to throw him off. Then later when Jon says to Death, "I could understand [my life turning out this way] it if I were a bad person, but I'm not," and Death just stares at him, there is a question about what kind of person Jon really is. Perhaps he is a bad person, perhaps he did a bad thing, but he tries not to remember it that way.

The first part of the book is filtered through the mind of the adult Jon. When he goes back to his town at the end of the book and sees himself playing football with Bjørn, their relationship is different from how he remembers it in the first part. Bjørn beats Jon easily and Jon appears to be angry. Maybe this is the dynamic between them that led to Jon tricking his friend into falling, and it's this that memory has blotted out. It's only when he can finally look at this truth that he is ready to board the bus.

In this respect, the figure of Death is also an aspect of Jon that he doesn't want to recognise. This is why, although the figure is antagonistic when they first meet, once Jon has set up the idea of the Batman club and the entry test, the Death figure smiles at him on his way by.

At the end Jon acknowledges and takes his rightful place amongst those figures who resemble the Death figure. He has always been amongst them, he just didn't want to see it.

That's where I'm at with it now.]]></wp:comment_content>
