			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2013-08-21 08:40:38</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[However, after much research, I can finally report that Frank’s comment about David Mazzucchelli’s theory of comics simultaneity (“The page is taken in as a whole, the two page spread. It’s not one image at a time. And it’s not necessarily linear in so much that it’s all absorbed at once and then accepted as ‘ordered.’”) is absolutely spot on. At least when you’re reading Mazzucchelli comics. It’s kind of amazing really. It works with everything from Batman to Asterios Polyp . I don’t know how he does it, but it’s true: entire spreads enter the reader’s brain instantaneously.]]></wp:comment_content>
