			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[I didn't see this at all, Brenna, but I can see it now.  Your interpretation of The Dark Knight Rises is brilliant.  Your interpretation reveals your enviable knowledge of politics, sociology, psychology, and the media.  But I must say I saw something else.

Because I read different books and have a different field of reference, I have a different sense of what this film may have been about besides a fantastically loud future that contains an awesome flying machine stabled in the black, wet basement of a stately home occupied by two amazingly lucky characters whose lives contrast so dramatically the hapless lives of those who struggle to rise (including Batman for a while, which shows no one is safe from haplessness) from a well in which they have been  thrown by those who hate and fear them.

What a terrifyingly delightful thing it is to go to a movie: to step out of the sun and enter a dark room where such scary alternative world, vaguely representing aspects of our own, can be experienced for awhile.  But how meaningful is it intended to be?

I can see that this film may have a theme, although I'm not convinced that sending a message was its main purpose.  If I think about what that theme might be, I'd say it was the problem of action: the problem of manifesting an ideal in the field of time.  Whenever one has an idea and puts it into action, there will be results, some that the initiator may be able to control, some which s/he may not...and these unforeseen and often terrible results of a well-intentioned idea can be devastating to oneself and others...sometimes many, many others.  Batman, we learn at the very beginning, arrested his active life for a long time because he recognized his power created problems he had not intended to create.  He recognized that action is dangerous.

This made me like Batman.  He was great and he was humble.  He'd become a wise non-agent...but he stepped off his safe pedestal of non-agency to try to change things for the better one more time.  That he died doing "a far, far better thing" saved
him from any negative consequences of his action.

In sum, I enjoyed the fantasy.  I'm 61.  I went with my son who's 27, who enjoyed the action.  Is it not wonderful to go to the pictures and enjoy the same film differently?]]></wp:comment_content>
