	<item>
		<title>#109 Inspiration and Integration: Why Comics Can&#039;t Come of Age</title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2013/03/109-inspiration-and-integration-why-comics-cant-come-of-age/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Mar 2013 07:08:45 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.cssgn.org/?p=2547</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Comics seem to come of age every ten years or so as the art form responds to innovations from its practitioners. Some might point to the Golden Age of comics in the 1950s as a the moment when comics came of age; others might harken further back to George Herriman's Krazy Kat and Ignatz, or the introduction of that cinematic mouse with the rounded ears; some would ask us to look to the late-sixties surge of underground comix and there decidedly anti-insitutitional narratives; still others might point to Art Spiegelman's Maus as the moment comics came of age as a medium for storytelling. There are no doubt many meandering and insightful conversations to be had about when exactly comics, as a medium, came of age.

All this to say that coming of age is not always dependent on a reading of the subject. Sometimes, we need to think about how narrative forms, or design forms, architectures perhaps, come of age in response to the subject matter or the cultural context in which those architectures find themselves representing. Making connections between the evolution of a medium and the cultural evolutions surrounding them seems almost like a moot point. However, comics are one of the few media often described as responding to their cultural surroundings. They appear to come of age again and again, getting connected with multiple forms of other media wherein comics are often cited as inspiration for stylistic choices and narrative practices. In other words, we are quick to show how comics are like other media and, most often, we say that comics are like whatever dominant media are in the cultural conversation and themselves coming of age.

When newspapers and Yellow Journalism came of age, The Yellow Kid arrived fully formed with his witty smocked placard performing the kind of “literary” critique that drew attention to the dispositions between high and low journalism. As radio and the cinema began to establish themselves, Herriman’s Krazy Kat began testing the medium’s response to surrealism and the comedic syncopations of vaudeville and burlesque. Cinema brought with a more coherent relationship with its storyboards and animations. The arrival of digital CG shows us on the brink of yet another linkage between comics architectures and creative practices of cinematic representation. In short, as other media come of age, comics seem to respond by also coming of age at the same moment. They are both inspired by and influence on emerging visual media, in particular.

Coming of age narratives are ultimately about personal origin stories. Comics possess an atypical connection to the origin stories that signal both the architectures and the story-lines of emerging media, which themselves are searching for their own origin stories or coming of age in the eyes of mass culture.

The baseline point here is that comics are embedded in the fabric of twentieth-century and twenty-first century artistic practice, particularly so in the veins of the visual media that so dominate our environments. What we need to do is start critiquing the architectures of comics to see how they are responding to shifts in formative associations -- the kids aren't reading the same superman.

Perhaps the clearest signal that comics are coming of age in, well, a different age is the way they reveal their foundational architectures through practice. Instead of dissolving into the tactile and analogue world of the pen, comics coming of age in a new landscape are dissolving into the foundational 8-bit square.

<center><a href="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/20130327-001041.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full" src="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/20130327-001041.jpg" alt="20130327-001041.jpg" /></a></center>On the other hand, comics are the bedrock of new experiments that endeavor to make the old new again, making comics not into cinema but more like a video game:
<blockquote>Project Gamma features digital comics with embedded audio, which plays as readers browse or read through. The music and background adapts to both the events in the comic and the reader's behaviour. The project is an attempt to make reading a more immersive experience, like being inside a video game, according to Marvel executives. (<a href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2013/03/11/marvel-comics-digital.html?cmp=rss" target="_blank">source</a>)</blockquote>
It's telling that comics seem to come back to their roots in the golden age of radio in order to go forward and make themselves more akin to video games. We always configure comics around the cinema but they remain unbound, taking their coming of age narratives into new forums. Or are they old forms made new by that impetus to meld media so inherent in comics' text/image coherence?

Have comics come of age? Nope. Like superman they remain in a perpetual state of influence and integration. Remaining inert but constantly on the vanguard of an evolving cultural moment. Comics and the creative architectures associated with them resist coming of age and at the same time remain adaptable to and representative of the artistic innovations that mark the era.]]></content:encoded>
