			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2013-05-02 11:49:40</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[Great article, and one that really got me thinking.

I think you capture (once again) what I'm trying to get at it in my own comics perfectly. In particular, where you suggest that in drawing "not trying to capture the past or present it through rose coloured glasses, but to look for something in it that [I] can’t quite figure out" I thought you nailed it in a way that I hadn't been able to before. It also made me thinking of 'Once in a Lifetime' by Talking Heads, which other than being a favourite song of mine, evokes a sort of biographical bewilderment, set against the indifference and beauty of the world. I think it pretty much sums up the question I'm always asking of myself in my comics: 'how did I get here?'.

This comment makes me reflect on Warren's words about my approach to memoir. I've never been interested in doing 'straight' autobiography, that is 'this happened then this happened then I went there'. Rather I'm interested in the feeling of an event, or the affect of a place or time in my life. I think I see that in Warren's work, too, but perhaps I'm projecting.

Drawing in the way that I helps me ask this question because it allows me to explore affects and atmospheres. I never fail to be astonished when someone can get what I'm getting at in so few lines. A workmate of my girlfriend saw my new 'holiday' zine and apparently (I wasn't there at the time) was totally taken with how the lines evoked  all the feelings I was hoping they'd evoke. It's really, really humbling.

Reflecting on these thoughts, and the joy I take when people relate to my comic, there's something else I realise now, about my own work,  which is to do with the format it takes usually (the zine) and its relationship to the reader

I want to tell stories about the world that people can relate to, and from whom I can learn in return. I like that the medium of comics can be used to that. I think I'm pretty traditional in that respect - I'm interested in the beat of the panels, the composition etc. a way to deliver oblique ideas. So the material artefact of the zine is important to me for that reason.

So perhaps my adherence to a traditional narrative is what sets us apart? Not to say that Warren's comics don't seek to tell stories - 'Thickets', one of my favourite pieces of his, is a beautiful, complex ode to a neighbourhood- but that their immediacy and methods of doing so play out in a different way

Warren's drawings succeed so beautifully because it is the drawing itself that lives, the echo of his hand and pencil, and the enigmatic assemblages that emerge so wonderfully from there. And it's the inventiveness of Warren's drawing that keeps me coming back and that makes me want to engage and learn from his work.]]></wp:comment_content>
