	<item>
		<title>#165 We&#039;re Punk, Not Junk</title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2014/05/165-were-punk-not-junk/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 06 May 2014 04:10:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.cssgn.org/?p=3679</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Nope, yr junk. Plain and simple.

I, for one, am all for the margins. And not the margins that reflect a deep immersion in the histories, narratives, and mythology of comics and their production, but the margins that seek to impose themselves on the rigid, contrived, penis-oriented nerd-centred hierarchies of comics histories, narratives, and mythologies. I’m interested in the margins that seek to provoke, up-end, insult the integrity of the burgeoning comics canon.

To this end, I’ve been getting antsy about what I see as an increasing shift in comics toward the mainstream, especially in the academy. Intellectual conversations around comics are circulating widely through the hallways, onto introductory course syllabi, and comics scholarship is right out there with other trendy approaches like digital humanities. We’re all busily finding a place for comics in the cultural conversation, seeking to justify, explain, generally demystify what we see as an art form.

Comics “scholars” (as if that isn’t the grandest of oxymorons–right up there with Heavy Metal scholars and sociologists) would do well to remember Joe Strummer: “Authority is supposedly grounded in wisdom, but I could see from a very early age that authority was only a system of control and it didn’t have any inherent wisdom. I quickly realized that you either became a power or you were crushed.” Or, if you prefer a notable quotable closer to home, how about Walt Kelly, through Pogo: “We have met the enemy and he is us.”

Whenever I get antsy about anything, I return to punk music. The music itself, and the philosophy behind it. The title of this missive comes from a newspaper headline in which “punks” were upset that they had been unduly picked upon by police for inciting a riot. It’s an old headline and notable only because I raged about it at the time. I raged because the whole principle of being punk is that you are junk–that’s your only power. You reject acceptance in favour of the margins. You support only chaos and loudness. You break consciously away from anything that might suggest legitimacy. Above all, you don’t whine about being junk–you relish it.

Comics and the conversations around them would do well to be conscious of the medium’s parallel trajectory to music, particularly music on the margins. I don’t think comics relish their disposability anymore, and I think the academic conversations around comics and their increasing visibility in academic contexts has something to do with this sense of permanence creeping into comics production. Everyday it seems there’s a new comic that represents our current cultural situation better than ever–that stands as a marker for who we are and where we might be going–like Sex Criminals, say. My point is this: is anyone just reading comics anymore? Or have they been permanently remediated as a valuable form of cultural production.

There’s all sorts of similar narratives trajectories in music: rap / gansta rap / rock’n’roll / punk / emo / all onceoccupied the margins, represented the margins, but now seem a permanent fixture in the cultural conversation–when yr mother is singing Jay-Z, is it really cultural critique–was it ever–does that matter? I don’t think comics should concern themselves with their viability. I think comics should be disposable, and we would do well to treat them as such. They can have value as something disposable–they always have. The difference is that returning to a disposable comics culture would bring things more in line with that other casualty of the digital age: the mixed tape.

http://youtu.be/zu1V3R-Jpwo

The exchange among peers of cassette tapes, with their scrawled ledgers listing tunes has disappeared into the regulated and formalized world of Rdio playlists, iTunes geniuses, and the like. Getting a friend’s mixed tape was a way of connecting, and disconnecting, from the community; we didn’t have to like it, we didn’t have to commit, we could damn well throw it out. Unfortunately, we’re far too busy making our own mixed tapes and not really participating any longer in the politics of exchange and disposability that makes comics–and good, emerging music–different, marginal. Comics and the narratives around them have turned all Prog. Rock: King Crimson sweeping narratives, endless in scope and twisting, turning in virtuoso performance rather than catchy disposable summer hits we all remember. We’re all critique and “genius” without any real sense of what the implications of such discourses might be or the utter boredom of the ritual itself (what’s the sound of 10,000 comicbook nerds wanking: a Rush concert).

In closing, let’s crank it up; rev up the chainsaw and blow everything we’re doing up. Let’s think less about justifying, close reading, and establishing legitimacy or a canon and think more about a disposable making mixed tapes that mark particular junctures in the life of a critical bell curve. Let’s make sure that the critical conversations we have about comics are as disposable and unnecessary as the medium itself. Stop shoving comics where they don’t belong; you might ruin them. And most of all, stop whining about how comics are not junk; they’re junk–that’s what makes them so fucking awesome.

&lt;!-- RIP Dave Gregg: http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/music/Obituary+godfather+hardcore+punk/9683158/story.html --!&gt;]]></content:encoded>
