			<wp:comment_date>2014-05-18 04:31:54</wp:comment_date>
			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2014-05-18 11:31:54</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[It seems the problem with the idiot in the room is that he's trying to force superheroes into the definition of comics. McCloud at the time was just part of a collective effort to root out the cliché that "comics = superheroes".

I don't feel that superhero stories are kept out of serious discussions about comics, or particularly despised. In the Hooded Utilitarian's top 115 comics, admitedly a connoisseur's list, Lee &amp; Kirby's Fantastic Four is 10th and Dark Knight Returns is 18th, while Tintin is 15th and Tezuka's Phoenix is 33rd. That feels pretty generous to me. Of course I'm French, so superheroes don't have the same meaning to me, but what I mean is that American scholars and hipster fans usually recognize the importance of superhero comics in their love of the genre, and the real qualities of the good ones.

I understand that the definition is very broad and exceedingly arcane, but that's because the important part is reaching that definition, by including, one by one, all the forms comics can take, rather than letting consensus limit its scope. That's what made the book great at the time.
Asking to add superheroes or fun in the definition wouldn't really take the discussion in any meaningful direction.]]></wp:comment_content>
