			<wp:comment_date>2014-05-26 11:30:17</wp:comment_date>
			<wp:comment_date_gmt>2014-05-26 18:30:17</wp:comment_date_gmt>
			<wp:comment_content><![CDATA[I'd say that seriousness about a medium also grows out of a love and deep appreciation of said medium, though, and that it warrants a certain (perhaps sometimes excessive) analysis. A discussion about comics that focuses on "Batman! Batman! Batman!" doesn't really lead to much except comic-book-store debates about which superhero could beat the Dark Knight (and boy, have I ever been there!). :-)

But isn't there also a little irony in writing a literary article about how comics shouldn't be taken too seriously? Are similar discussions about literature too serious?

I think McCloud also was trying to define too many things as belonging to the world of comics, that much is true, and his definition is probably too vague to be all that useful on a practical level. However, I don't believe that comics need to be fun. They certainly CAN be, and in many cases should be, but many of the greatest comics are not fun per se; I don't know that I'd call all that much of Alan Moore's work "fun" (Top Ten and such notwithstanding), but V for Vendetta and Watchmen are some of my favourite comics.

Another point I'd like to mention is that those people who "really matter to the future of comics" are in large part the people maintaining the status quo of comics with regard to the representation of women and other minorities in the medium. They're not, by and large, the ones interested in having debates over heteronormativity in comics or pushing for the retirement of tired tropes like the Women in the Refrigerator and such. Given that, I'd argue that MORE room ought to be reserved for "ivory tower dorks" like us.]]></wp:comment_content>
