	<item>
		<title>#189 OK, This &#034;Looks&#034; Bad, But...</title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2014/12/189-ok-this-looks-bad-but/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 18 Dec 2014 19:56:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.cssgn.org/?p=4062</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[This post features an Easter Egg--a hidden clue to its complete reading. We're riding the edge of the wave here, but trying to think about the hidden aspects of collaboration; the visual verses the unseen. So, half of this post is hidden from <strong>view</strong> unless you search for it. It's not hard to find; one hint: you need to <strong>view</strong> what's hidden in the page--not simply what's visible--the "<strong>source</strong>."

Collaboration, in comics as elsewhere, helps us to reframe our static perspectives <!-- One such "static perspective" is only looking at surfaces and not being aware of the underlying secrets the platform might reveal -->– Graphixia has helped me do this a lot by getting me to approach comics in a more academic way through the suggestions offered by my peers, putting more esoteric fare in my hands than I’m normally gravitated towards. Rarely though do I need someone to tempt me to read a superhero book, as I read practically everything I can get my hands on (I’ve written about my disturbingly large collection here before). But then Dave started writing about Hawkeye and suggesting it to others.

<!-- The irony of this statement is that in the beginning, at least as far as I was concerned, Scott was the most academic among us. His contributions to Graphixia certainly reflect more attention to the historiography and facts of comics than any one of us. Like in his daily life, Scott is the head librarian at Graphixia, someone who takes a lot of time and care to get the facts correct. I'm flattered that he even thought to listen to anything I had to say.-->

Personally, I’ve never been a fan of the character. Hawkeye has existed in many iterations since his first appearance in Tales of Suspense in the 60’s. Mostly, he was the Iron Man nobody wanted, out of place on a team of heroes imbued with fantastic powers and with writers unsure of what to do with him. What good is an archer against hordes of aliens, against villains with mystical powers – against, very often, gods? There was perhaps a certain everyman potential about him, but even this was masked early on by writers stamping his carnival-esque character as a womanizing alcoholic, likely because if they couldn’t emphasize his powers to make him interesting, at least they could amplify some titillating flaws. <!--See, this is exactly what I was talking about above. He knows EVERYTHING about a character he's not that interested in. I had no idea about Hawkeye. I was completely clueless that such a character existed before the Aja / Fraction collaboration.-->

Regardless, I collected Hawkeye in the 80’s and early 90’s with his four issue mini-series (a way of testing if the market will bear a longer running solo title. It didn’t), and his eight issue attempt at a run in the early 00’s. I still have all the issues, but I never read them more than once. The only time that Hawkeye ever became interesting for me was when Brian Michael Bendis got ahold of him during his run on New Avengers, but even then the only way to draw people in to his character was to kill him then completely reinvent him – he had Hawkeye pose as a different masked, martial-arts based character, Ronin, for a large portion of the series, with the big reveal that it was Hawkeye who had been masquerading as a ninja ultimately coming as a bit of a letdown once he went back to the quiver and rejoined the team. He immediately went back to being second string.

So, history dispensed with, when I saw Hawkeye reappear on my monthly list of potential new titles, I skipped it altogether. When Dave wrote his superfluous<!--This is one interesting piece to collaboration: interpretation. Does Scott mean "superfluous" or is that a typo for superb? Was the post superfluous? What the hell is he saying? He's right of course, it was superfluous, but superbly so. This kind of interpretation of another's ideas is a central claim of collaboration. One that's even more interesting because the interpretation, at least in the case of Fraction and Aja, is marked by a translation of words into images, or sketches into "drawings." There's bound to be tons of these interpretive miscues, but they're hidden in the final product--the polished, reviewed, and properly constructed artifice. Of course, this is what I think's interesting about "commenting out" my contribution here, because ultimately, collaboration is all about plummeting the process into secrecy and revealing only the product.--> Pizza Dog article, I got a little more intrigued. When I saw that the comics had jumped in value quite a bit I kicked myself. And when I finally picked up and read the first trade (with the clerk telling me “oh Hawkeye! That’s a great series”), I was more than a little irritated that I’d let my previous experience with the character get in the way of seeing him through what turned out to be a provocative new lens. <!--Show you: always be open. Experience is a dreadful thing-->And comics has a way of doing this, experimenting with characters who have fallen out of favour by adding new creative teams (to make a recommendation of my own, the currently running Silver Surfer helmed by heavy hitters Dan Slott and Mike Allred exemplifies exactly the same scenario).<!-- I totally agree with this recommendation. Great series so far.-->

And, to be fair, this isn’t Hawkeye. It can barely be called Clint Barton. Matt Fraction and David Aja <!--Always interesting to me how many people get excluded from the collaborative team. Matt Hollingsworth's work on Hawkeye is total genius. But, most people don't acknowledge his contribution to the product. The colour palette for Hawkeye has been one of the bright spots in the collaboration to my mind. Also of note, this is the same team that did Immortal Iron Fist a few years back and they rip a lot of their artistic attitude from the way they approached that series. So, there's some precedence for what they're up to that's hidden unless you know where to look. And this is another thing about collaboration that's worth thinking about--how collaboration is often a kind of build up of historical precedents about working together and interpreting each other's moves. All that stuff is hidden, but it's central to the outcomes. Getting the right people to do the right things.-->getting their hands on the old, dusty franchise character were given rarely offered complete creative control over him; and really, when everyone expected the book to fail given the <strong>source</strong> material, why not dabble in a way that really allows for the team’s collaborative voice to come through? They’re seemingly aware of the challenge as well - the repeated first line of every issue, “Okay, this looks bad,” punningly references whatever awkward situation has been constructed for Hawkeye but also working with the character himself, the two creators tasked every issue with capturing their readers’ interest with no one’s favorite Avenger. As Fraction <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/hawkeye-matt-fraction_n_3613441.html">himself stated</a>, "It's the book that should not exist, so why not take the chances and do the experimenting?" And have they ever – from near silent issues told from the perspective of Hawkeye’s rescued dog to issues told entirely in sign language, Hawkeye has gone out of its way to highlight the talents of both writer and artist<!-- and colourist!! Take a look at the colour scheme for the Pizza Dog issue and the visible colour spectrum for a canine. MIND BLOWN! That Hollingsworth is a masterful bastard-->, almost to the degree that you have to admit that the character is really just along for the ride – we see this expressed literally again and again, as he’s picked up in different vehicles and driven around by Young Avenger Kate Bishop, then by SHEILD, then by the mob, then offscreen by Tony Stark, always totally confused and directionless. I’ve never seen a comic that so obviously and actively refuses to let the character have any agency whatsoever, nearly breaking the fourth wall at points in order to do so.

This is, perhaps, a way of indicating that whatever Hawkeye turns out to be, they’re willing to own it for better or worse.<!-- Of note too is that Hawkeye doesn't actually do much Superhero-ing in this series. It's all about his everyday life--very Seinfeld in approach. The series de-emphasizes that very thing it would seem to need to reboot. In other words, you reboot the franchise that features a Superhero with lame powers by avoiding the showcasing of those lame powers.--> Fraction’s comedic turn with his tracksuit dracula “bros” (one can’t help but think this is a current pop culture reference to Pewdiepie and his “bro army”) and his consistent gesturing towards the zaniness of the life of a superhero as told from the perspective of the regular guy makes us engage more with Fraction than with Clint – again, he’s always getting himself into trouble, avoiding problems and never quite knowing what to say. Unlike most superhero comics, in Hawkeye instead it’s the situation rather than the character that drives the plot, and they emphasize this by even having him miss his targets in close range target practice.<!--For sure a metaphor for how often this series has missed its own targets. The final issues have been delayed and delayed and delayed, now due out in January and February 2015. Hidden dialects again... Fraction's too busy on his other collaboration with Chip to be bothered with Hawkeye. --> Clint does have brief moments of heroism, but really, he could be any of us. Very frequently he tells his neighbors to ignore the fact that he’s “Hawkguy.” It’s almost as if, throughout, Fraction has found a way to write anything but a superhero comic while making sure that it sells as it’s under the Marvel brand name. Even when he does introduce the rest of the Marvel Universe, he dispenses with it immediately by first having Clint black out for the duration of the fight then by having him take a vacation.

Looking at the same scene, Aja’s gritty but still simplified style, reminiscent of David Mazzucchelli’s Batman run,<!--Scott being Scott again. I hadn't even thought of that connection, but dammit if Scott didn't. And he's totally correct. --> compliments the refusal to adhere to the genre as he pans back from action shots to make the even the violence look, in a way, pathetic. <!--Also very reminiscent of Steranko's run on Nick Fury. That's where Aja gets a lot of his cool broken action stuff. --> Barton is always getting hurt, as we rarely see heroes suffer (a broken pelvis? With three weeks’ recovery? Ow), but Aja draws it in such a way to emphasize Clint’s fragility – we’re deprived of the momentous “pows” and “biffs” of the superhero fight scene, as Clint is beaten without fanfare in small frames, often caught off guard, frequently being knocked immediately unconscious. As acknowledged in the many, many podcasts and inter<strong>view</strong>s with the pair (<a href="http://traffic.libsyn.com/decompressed/Decompressed004.mp3">here's one</a>), Fraction is playing to Aja’s talents as they play with every facet of the medium, experimenting with transitions, hiding gags throughout and generally having a lot of fun. <!--There's also the visual signatures of Aja in the comic to go along with Fraction's own self-referential humour. The band-aid on the nose and cheek is something Aja did on his Immortal Iron Fist run and it carries over even into the New Avengers run lately. The visual signature that sends us back to Aja. It's another cool hidden allusion that signals not only Aja, but his collaboration with Hollingsworth and Fraction on Immortal Iron Fist previously.-->

And if Hawkeye is about anything, it’s this – giving a pair with the credentials behind them a low stakes outlet to experiment with style, with dialogue and with content without potentially upsetting Marvel’s broader fanbase. They play to the mythos only as much as it suits them, which is likely why is hasn’t ostracized readers unfamiliar with the genre, which is likely why Dave found it so appealing<!--I found it appealing because the drawing was awesome and the storylines, to me, reflected a direct reference to the reader's tendency to judge things before they actually engage with them. Like Scott did for instance. It seemed to me, as Scott has noted, that there was an ironic finger to the reader with the "this looks bad" line. As if they new readers wouldn't want to read it. And then they put together a really superior product. It also appealed to me because the comic reflected a kind of elitist / indie band attitude in its construction. Aja was really slow; Fraction didn't seem to really give a shit; Hollingsworth is a dude; and so on. The comic was an uncomic and more about a bunch of guys playing in a garage on Sunday. I wish we had more books like this one and I wish the ladies would get together and do one for Kate Bishop's Hawkeye.--> and why I was averse to it at first. But though this has been something of an experiment and though it’s not likely to be canon anytime soon, they’re opening up the door for more creativity to be brought to the superhero comic, providing it with an infusion of vitality that, as we’ve noted at graphixia, is much needed if they’re to remain relevant to a broader audience.

<!--And so we end. Hidden contributions and final constructions. It's not always about interpreting the surfaces and the significations indicated by such surfaces. Sometimes, there's the hidden or even, dare I say it, excluded interfaces of collaboration--I'm looking at you Stan Lee. And, I think we always need to think about the hidden cultural interfaces of collaboration. For instance, how does race, gender, and our collective understanding of these things--the ingrained presence of those kinds of cultural assumptions--distort how we collaborate with others? Do we seek out our own kind, or do we seek out others? In the case of Hawkeye, I think they sought out there own. What we need is a different kind of collaboration--so, a Jew, a black woman, and a bhuddist start writing a comicbook...-->]]></content:encoded>
