		<title>#194 Erasure: The Soviet-era Komik  </title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2015/02/194-erasure-the-soviet-era-komik/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Feb 2015 19:04:23 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.cssgn.org/?p=4117</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Full confession: I haven't done a lot of reading for this post; I'm going purely on instinct and a desire to start the conversation not "weigh in" on it like some well-informed zealot. The bottom line is that I couldn't find many comics that covered what I wanted to address: Soviet-era komiksky. The materials are scant, supposedly as a result of a cultural impetus away from the trapping of Westernized ideology--I guess the Kremlin didn't really get that Superman was basically a communist from outer-space. Even if I managed to find something, getting my hands on it was next to impossible. The history of the Soviet-era komik is an invisible or erased one, which of course seems now like an entirely suitable topic.

The politics of erasure in comics is often a popular subject. Erasure is in fact what makes some comics so valuable--the disposability and pulp of comics often causes examples to be erased from existence. When one example is found, its value is determined by the number of other examples that don't exist. But what if we were to direct our gaze to where comics are not? Could we even conceive of what we are not looking for? It's never struck me more that comics are Western in every politically, economically, and socially loaded way. They tend to idealize the Western mindset that suggests freedom from purgatory is the only option for one's existence, despite never really addressing how the beached fish even knows the water is purgatory. At the same time, comics utilize a mode of production that, at least until recently, relies on the disposability of its tactile representation, and the repetition of its narratives; a Westernized advertising strategy that echoes the Fordian efficiency of the assembly-line if there ever was one: "you can have any superhero you want, as long as its a Capitalist." In short, erasure is a common thread the spins out of the button and to some extent releases comics from accountability. As long as we don't look at comics long enough, or don't have access to comics that reflect a different political, social, or economic agenda, everything will be fine.

Sometimes, there's a pre-determined perspective that governs the study of comics. Because the "discipline" is nascent, sort of, we're allowed to get away with all kinds of pretty myopic textual choices. For instance, one of the reasons we're doing this sequence on "foreign" comics is to broaden our view, but I for one was guilty of not really accounting for the mere availability of comics outside the cultural mainframe (what? there's nothing on comixology? What do I do now!?). Most often, comics scholarship has a real need to establish its domain of interrogation, in structuralist terms, by laying into the most voluminous material which, it so happens, is usually North American and Japanese in origin. At best it's a delightful mix of Anglo-American, White European, and Asian texts providing plenty of fodder for the adventurous and canonical among us. At worst it discounts other perspectives--political, economic, cultural--in favour of aggrandizing a set of values that seem to be reinforced by the genre's own heroic values. In short, we are what we read.

All of which brings me to the communists. While abhorring everything to do with the Bourgeois West, the Soviets put the kibosh on any comic book best sellers in the republic. But one can't help but wonder what a comic book from the Soviets would look like. The cold war truth is that we may never know what that might have looked like. Even now, the archives prioritize narratives such as Nikolai Maslov's "Siberia" that shows a desolate and bleak worldview of the Russian state in which the main character wanders through a Dantean Inferno of a Soviet system eventually going insane. Everything about Maslov's book, the bleak storyline, the sketchy pencil drawing, the deeply introspective bent, the historiographic gaze backward, belongs to the structuralist triggers of the Western comics cannon for "arty" autobiography--Spiegleman, Satrapi, Crumb, Bechdel, Barry (ugh); <a href="http://www.empireonline.com/features/die-hard-movies-that-arent-die-hard/p4" target="_blank"><em>Die Hard</em> with a pencil.</a>

If I have a point, it's this: where's our gaze directed? And why? I'm not suggesting that the persecuted individual without freedoms should not be saved by the freedom-loving potential of a comicbook. Absolutely, I'm pro comics that help those in shitty situations overcome those shitty situations, however marginal that "help" might be. At the same time, if comics are as universal as comics scholars often suggest that they are, then what are the conditions of that universality. Taking a cue from the recent bent toward <a href="https://www.google.ca/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&ion=1&espv=2&ie=UTF-8#q=broken%20world%20thinking" target="_blank">"Broken World Thinking,"</a> comics are not produced in an economic, political, or cultural vacuum, and we do a pretty good job of talking about how comics under-represent women, minorities, etc. But what about the comics we can't see? And, what about those cultural, economic, and political situations that prohibit the very existence of comics? What about that situation? How do we even understand that situation? Can we, even? Should we, even? (This is all very Duchamp all of a sudden... <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bride_Stripped_Bare_by_Her_Bachelors,_Even" target="_blank">he liked it better broken.</a>)

In the end, what exercises like this one tell me is that there's a whole lotta stuff out there that's been erased; not "just" silenced. Restoring erasure is way harder than restoring silences, and that's something comics might need to grapple with -- that erasure is built into the political, economic, and cultural apparatus of comics themselves.]]></content:encoded>
