		<title>#205 On Alpha Flight, Canada, and Indigenous Appropriation</title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2015/05/205-on-alpha-flight-canada-and-indigenous-appropriation/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 26 May 2015 18:29:55 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Grayb]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.cssgn.org/?p=4313</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Graphixians, I am writing a conference paper this week, which means that you get to read my uncollected thoughts towards a conference paper. Aren't you lucky ducks, one and all.

As the title suggests, I'm thinking a lot about the way mainstream American comics signal "Canadianness" by appropriating indigenous characters as symbolic of north. I came to this by way of Jason Dittmer and Soren Larsen's article "Aboriginality and the Arctic North in Canadian Nationalist Superhero Comics, 1940-2004." It's a really interesting look at the way comics producers in Canada, especially in the Canadian Whites era and with Captain Canuck, used arctic imagery and (deeply problematic) representations of First Nations people in order to code comics and situations as specifically Canadian. I really enjoyed the article and I like Jason Dittmer's work particularly, and build upon it a lot in other contexts.

But the article takes a turn that I think lacks some context, and that is to include without critical reflection Alpha Flight in the annals of the nationalist superheroes of Canada. I know where this comes from in the context of Alpha Flight scholarship: Bart Beaty's "The Fighting Civil Servant" article, wherein he makes an argument for Alpha Flight as being more successful at representing Canadian region and more successful as a viable comic book than the aggressively nationalist efforts like Captain Canuck. But Beaty's reading is nuanced in a way that critics who have come after it have failed to note: Alpha Flight is not an expressly nationalist comic book. Its primary goal is not to represent Canada or achieve something meaningful to Canadian identity, but to be entertaining enough to sell well enough in the United States to stay on comic book stands.

Alpha Flight is certainly an all-Canadian superhero team created by an expatriate Canadian, but it's not itself a Canadian comic -- as part of Marvel's comic book juggernaut, Alpha Flight always had to serve its corporate master first. (It's worth reading the letter pages in those early Alpha Flight comics to see what I mean. Readers who complained about a lack of geographic or cultural accuracy in the comic were roundly slapped down for misunderstanding that the comic was fiction.)

Alpha Flight is definitely part of the tradition of nationalist comics in that John Byrne was certainly influence by Nelvana of the North, and that aspect of Dittmer and Larsen's article holds true. But it's worth thinking about how Alpha Flight uses indigineity to signal Canadianness to an American audience in the form of Snowbird and Shaman whose powers are deeply connected to that land. Indeed, Snowbird loses her power when she leaves Canada, imposing a colonial border upon her and universalizing her indigenous identity as being specifically Canadian (deeply ironic given the current challenges some First Nations have in being recognized as superseding imposed nation-state boundaries).

<a href="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/0910_snowbird.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-4315" src="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/0910_snowbird.jpg" alt="0910_snowbird" width="600" height="399" /></a>

It's an appropriation of First Nations spirituality to represent Shaman and Snowbird in these contexts, and we need to be mindful of the fact that although Alpha Flight's diversity is laudable for its historical context, it's part of a larger history of white comic artists depicting First Nations characters for thematic ends. In the case of Alpha Flight, it's also about defining Canada in terms that are distinct from the US. The foregrounding of Native characters suggests a different kind of relationship to the land, nation, and north than is exhibited by, say, the X-Men, the superhero team Alpha Flight is most commonly either fighting with or against.

This question is particularly salient given the 2014 launch of another Canadian superhero – and another appropriation of aboriginal identity – by Marvel’s competitor DC for their <em>Justice Unlimited</em> series by Canadian artist Jeff Lemire (famous in Canada for his <em>Essex County</em>). Again, we see mainstream American representations of Canadian identity coded through the appropriation of First Nations culture, this time in the character of Equinox. Lemire’s attempt is more delicate and nuanced, but still makes assumptions about Canadian identity as inherently indigenous.

[caption id="attachment_4314" align="aligncenter" width="600"]<a href="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/koostachinandequinox.jpg"><img class="wp-image-4314" src="http://www.graphixia.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/koostachinandequinox.jpg" alt="It's worth noting that Equinox is a literal appropriated of a real woman, the late Shannen Koostachin of Attawapiskat." width="600" height="294" /></a> It's worth noting that Equinox is a literal appropriation of a real woman, the late Shannen Koostachin of Attawapiskat.[/caption]

The task of the paper is two-fold: to unpack Alpha Flight from this assumption about it as a nationalist title, and to trace the use of indigeneity to code Canadian superhero teams and titles as other-than in the context of mainstream American comics.

Now I just have to write it.]]></content:encoded>
