Ernesto: <strong><span data-sheets-value="[null,2,&quot;EP. The Thrilling Adventures of Lovelace and Babbage: The (Mostly) True Story of the First Computer, by Sydney Padua &quot;]" data-sheets-userformat="[null,null,513,[null,0],null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,0]"><em>The Thrilling Adventures of Lovelace and Babbage: The (Mostly) True Story of the First Computer</em> by Sydney Padua.</span></strong>

Scott: <span data-sheets-value="[null,2,&quot;Miracleman with Neil Gaiman and Mark Buckingham. I collected this way back when Gaiman took over for Alan Moore years ago, when the title was originally published by Eclipse - to see Gaiman back at the helm after decades is fantastic, as he has an inimitable turn of phrase that make you reflect on the importance of minor events by applying these beautiful abstractions that, once you see them, make it difficult to go back to the way you thought before. Beautifully written and drawn, unfortunately polybagged so I have to buy two of every issue. - SM&quot;]" data-sheets-userformat="[null,null,513,[null,0],null,null,null,null,null,null,null,null,0]"><strong><em>Miracleman</em> with Neil Gaiman and Mark Buckingham.</strong> I collected this way back when Gaiman took over for Alan Moore years ago, when the title was originally published by Eclipse - to see Gaiman back at the helm after decades is fantastic, as he has an inimitable turn of phrase that make you reflect on the importance of minor events by applying these beautiful abstractions that, once you see them, make it difficult to go back to the way you thought before. Beautifully written and drawn, unfortunately polybagged so I have to buy two of every issue.</span>

