	<item>
		<title>#232 I&#039;ve Nothing to Say</title>
		<link>http://www.graphixia.ca/2016/04/232-ive-nothing-to-say/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Apr 2016 04:35:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Grayb]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.graphixia.ca/?p=4730</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I've nothing to say, dear Graphixians. I've nothing to say.

And yet, here I am, typing away to you late on a Tuesday. Because it's my week to post, you see. And because Graphixia is something I've been keeping up my commitment to for the last five years. And because that commitment is valuable.

But I've nothing to say.

It's been an up-and-down kind of five years, academically-speaking. I've had successes and failures, and I've accomplished lots of really great things and failed to accomplish much, much greater things. But in spite of new positions attained and books unfinished, I'm still a Graphixian. There's not much else that has felt constant about my identity as an academic in these first years post-PhD, but I've been a Graphixian for most of them. That means a lot to me.

I didn't think of myself as a comics scholar when I joined Graphixia. I do now. 250, 500, 1000 words at a time, I wrote towards a new academic identity, one that has simultaneously welcomed and infuriated me -- like any true family, I suppose.

Because of Graphixia, I've been asked to contribute to book collections and encyclopedias, give invited talks, help organize a conference, travel, present at conferences, act as a peer reviewer, serve on an editorial board, and edit a collection. 250, 500, 1000 words at a time I've written myself a tiny corner of expertise that is mine, and that people know is mine, and that stands apart from any work I did as a graduate student.

My adult identity as a scholar is as much a product of Graphixia as of my education.

Someone wise -- well, Peter -- once said that we should never underestimate the power of short, consistent, committed writing practice. This is an innovation to my workflow that the Graphixia project has given me, and it has made for a productive five years. 250, 500, 1000 words at a time, I have written and published more, both for scholarly and popular sources, in the last five years than in any other period in my life.

Someone wise -- well, Dave -- once said that doing the work publicly is important, too. Tomorrow, someone is going to interview me about <a href="http://tinyletter.com/brenna">my TinyLetter</a>, wherein I am often very open and public about my failings, shortcomings, and anxieties as a junior scholar. I learned how to do that, too, at Graphixia. To float a theory in 250, 500, 1000 words at a time, because I have 45 minutes and no one else to float the idea to but you, Graphixians. I have written my way into good arguments and bad ones, ones I am proud to own and ones I cringe at now. But they're all mine, and they're all here, and they're all part of the narrative of my journey as a scholar.

Never believe people who seem to know what they're doing all the time. They're lying to you. Trust people who fail staggeringly, spectacularly in public. Then help them pick themselves up and start again.

It has been a crushing semester. I'm terribly tired.

This month, Graphixians, I've nothing to say.

But the lesson of Graphixia is knowing that 250, 500, 1000 words at a time, I will. Eventually.]]></content:encoded>
